# Quality Gate (PostFlow)

Run these three steps after completing ANY phase, feature, or non-trivial change.
This gate is not optional. A phase is not done until all three steps pass.

================================================================
STEP 1 — PRE-SHIP CHECKS
================================================================
□ Code compiles — no TypeScript errors, no lint violations
□ Test suite passes (npm test)
□ No console errors or unhandled promise rejections
□ No TODOs, FIXMEs, or commented-out code in shipped files
□ Every public code path has error handling (null inputs, network failure, API errors)
□ All async operations wrapped in try/catch or .catch()

================================================================
STEP 2 — MODULARITY & ARCHITECTURE
================================================================
□ Business logic lives in src/lib/ — NOT in API routes or components
□ Each module/function has ONE clear responsibility (describable without "and")
□ No new circular dependencies introduced
□ New tables/columns: `nt()` cast used for untyped rows; types regeneration noted
□ All queries use `postflow` schema — never `public`
□ Layer separation maintained: route → lib → DB (no shortcuts)

================================================================
STEP 3 — LESSONS & DECISIONS
================================================================
□ Any mistake corrected during this phase → add pattern to tasks/lessons.md
□ Any architectural decision made → add to tasks/decisions.md
□ Any new UI component pattern → add to memory/ui_ux_patterns.md
□ Any new DB table or column → note types regeneration needed

================================================================
QUALITY STANDARD
================================================================
The bar is not "it works." The bar is "a staff engineer would approve this."
- Edge cases handled (empty, null, error, concurrent)
- Tests prove behavior, not just that code runs
- Code supports future expansion without major refactoring
- Documentation explains WHY, not just WHAT

If any Step 1 or Step 2 item fails: fix it before marking done.
Do not defer critical issues — that iteration never comes.
